When we copy a filter then the copied filter is displayed in default columns. There should be some option to also copy columns from the filter.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-30955].
  {panel}

Currently, JIRA filters able to run/save as single JQL query in Issue Navigator. As a user it will be great to create a filter that is comprised of other filters and therefore we can build up the filters we need.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-30950].
  {panel}

As of now, we are all aware of the usage of the horizontal scroll bar that allows the user to scroll to the right for long code blocks:
{code}
testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing testing 
{code}

Is it possible to have an *option* to choose whether the text is displayed in a single line or *wrap up* the text and show them without the horizontal scroll bar?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-30948].
  {panel}

An example would be like the following:
!jql_result.JPG!

This will be helpful to monitor the *health* and *status* of issues that are not on schedule or needs more attention.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Cloud*. Using *JIRA Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRASERVER-30947].
  {panel}

Currently saving a filter provides a confirmation, but does not provide the ability to undo your last save or to step through the history of the filter.

If filters were versioned, it would make it possible to revert unintended changes or see the evolution of search approaches.

This is particularly relevant for filters that are used as the basis of shared dashboard gadgets, where an entire organization might be viewing a single filter.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
