A workflow we commonly use on our team is that issues transition through from "open" to "done" (with some steps in between) and if / when bugs are found with the change the issue is re-opened so it can be evaluated further. It would be nice to have a summary metric, say calculated per sprint / iteration, that showed the total number of DIs that entered each state per sprint.

The sample workflow would look something like this: issue is created, assessed and worked upon via one or more state transitions (e.g.: open->analysing->in progress) and it get re-assigned to another team member for final testing and validation (e.g.: by setting it to a "testing" state). A bug is found with the implementation and so the issue is re-opened. If a large number of issues fall into this category, say 50%, it indicates possible problems earlier in the workflow which may suggest possible workflow improvements (e.g.: perhaps the requirements were unclear or the implementation was not up to par). By being able to measure the total number of issues per-sprint that transitioned at some point to the "re-opened" state it allows leads to spot such issues much easier.

As mentioned on my somewhat related DI JIRA-30900, there may be some alternate means through which we can calculate such a metric (scripts, third-party plugins, etc.) but I have not found any yet. I am open to suggestions. However, ideally this would be an integrated feature in Jira not requiring any special configuration.

